what is a fixed priority arbiter ?
A Fixed Priority Arbiter is an arbitration logic that always grants access based on a predefined, 
constant priority order among multiple requesters.

ğŸ“Œ Definition
In a fixed priority arbiter:
Each requester has a static priority
Highest-priority active request always wins
Priority never changes at runtime

ğŸ” Example (4 requesters)
Assume priority order:
req[3] > req[2] > req[1] > req[0]   (req[3] is highest)

If inputs are:
req = 4'b1011   // req[3], req[1], req[0] active

Then output:
grant = 4'b1000  // req[3] gets grant

Lower-priority requests are ignored even if theyâ€™ve been waiting longer.

ğŸ§  How it works (conceptually)
Check highest-priority request
If asserted â†’ grant it
Else check next priority

ğŸ§¾ Simple Verilog Example (Combinational)
always @(*) begin
  grant = 4'b0000;
  if (req[3])      grant = 4'b1000;
  else if (req[2]) grant = 4'b0100;
  else if (req[1]) grant = 4'b0010;
  else if (req[0]) grant = 4'b0001;
end


| Feature    | Fixed Priority   | Round-Robin |
| ---------- | -------------- --| ----------- |
| Priority   | Static           | Dynamic     |
| Fairness   | âŒ Poor         | âœ… Good      |
| Starvation | âŒ Yes          | âŒ No        |
| Complexity | âœ… Low          | âŒ Higher    |



Continue until one request is found
